comments.text:
1. find a bootable Linux installation media
2. boot into it
3. open terminal
4. type "lsblk", press enter, and identify your boot/linux partition
5. if you are unsure which device is your boot partition, type "sudo blkid /dev/sdxX" (replace sdxX with the actual device name from lsblk) and press enter (do this until you find your boot device)
5. type "sudo e2fsck -f /dev/sdxX", replace xX with what you saw in the lsblk command (i.e. if your boot/linux partition was sda1, replace sdxX with sda1)
6. press enter and wait (this command will perform a file system check and attempt repairs, please be patient and let it fix stuff)
7. reboot, remove installation media if prompted
